The big return of the Czech disaster is approaching.
Pavel Francouz has been called up to the NHL
Czech ice hockey goaltender Pavel Francouz, who is going through a difficult period of his career in recent months, is returning to the NHL.
The 31-year-old Plzeň native will be on the bench and could soon be in the goal.
The former goaltender for Litvínov, Pilsen and the Russian Chelyabinsk was injured in preparation for the NHL in October this year.
He was replaced at exactly the halfway point of the game against Vegas and has not appeared on an NHL ice sheet since.
The incident happened as the experienced goalkeeper moved from one post to the other.
"Pavel Francouz will be out for approximately three to four weeks with a lower-body injury," the team announced in early October.
His return to the NHL crease eventually stretched to more than two months.
He was called up from the farm on Sunday morning American time, where he caught four duels and showed his old form.
In the AHL, he posted a 94.5% save percentage.
The Pilsen-born hockey player wants to finally break through and confirm that he belongs in the best league in the world.
He had hip problems last year and didn't play a single game in the shortened pandemic season.
In the NHL, "Francík" played 36 games, with a success rate of 92.3%.
