According to efotbal.cz, Slavia promised Berbr a million for the title, which Tvrdík denied.
Prague - The investigators in the current corruption case are allegedly working on the assumption that the accused former deputy chairman of the Czech Football Association, Roman Berbr, was promised one million Czech crowns by the Prague Slavia for the league title in the 2018/19 season.
The website efotbal.cz informed about it and said that it had access to part of the police files.
The chairman of the board of the Vršovice club, Jaroslav Tvrdík, said that the white-and-reds did not engage in any corrupt behaviour.
The website published transcripts of police wiretaps, in which Slavia is mainly represented by its former sporting director, Jan Nezmar, who left the club last summer.
According to the indictment, the former influential official of the red-and-whites was in frequent contact with Berbra and with the former sports director of the then second-division club Vyšehrad, Roman Rogoz, who is also among the accused in the case.
The police were reportedly working with information that Slavia had promised Berbatov a financial reward for winning the title.
In 2019, SK Slavia Prague won the first league title.
The police authority was aware that Roman (Berbr) had been promised a million-dollar bribe by the officials of SK Slavia Prague for winning the league, the server quoted from the file.
The following day, according to the investigators, Berbr met not only with Nezmar, but also with the chairman of the board of directors of Slavia, Tvrdík.
According to the website, it is no longer clear from the file whether the police are still dealing with this information.
Tvrdík denied any corrupt dealings.
Between 2015 and 2017, we actively tried to change the situation in Czech football and offered an alternative to its development.
We have never committed any illegal acts, we have never tried to influence referees against the rules of fair play, and we have never provided anyone with any financial benefits in this regard," said Tvrdík for Seznam Zprávy.
In the recordings, Nezmar, among other things, indiscriminately insults some former dark-skinned Slavia players and also defames his former boss, Tvrdík.
The case of alleged match-fixing through referees was sparked by a police raid in the middle of October last year at several locations, including the FAČR headquarters in Prague.
The highest-ranking official in the scandal is Berbr, who is no longer involved in any football functions.
In mid-January, he was released from custody, just like the former Vyšehrad sports director Rogoz.
