Lenka Kabrhelová speaks to iRozhlas editor Dominika Kubištová.
I respect soldiers and the army (perhaps I am not affected by memories of the Czechoslovak People's Army, which the older generation went through), but the Czech Republic cannot benefit from compulsory military service.
We don't even have large stores of equipment that could be grabbed by the trained, we don't even have modern equipment for the current professionals, plus modern equipment is always more complex, so the abilities of the reserves will be rapidly lost over time.
On top of that, modern conventional conflicts, where anyone can get involved, will play out very quickly, and there won't be time to retrain people.
And finally, the reserves/territorial defence are of great importance for countries such as Ukraine, where it is necessary to wage mass guerrilla warfare and it is also a stated necessity to deter the enemy.
In the Czech Republic, it will only be possible to fight a war of such scale and intensity that guerrilla warfare will be irrelevant, and we do not have the right geography for that.
Mainly, we don't have individual skills.
And that's not even the worst of it.
The worst thing is that half of them play like they have one.
Then you find yourself in situations where you're watching a guy who missed an open net 2 minutes ago, driving into a 2-on-2 or even a 3-on-2, and you say to yourself, "What the hell does he think is going to happen now?"
Of course, they will treat him like an average taxpayer.
The situation with this skill of "beating a defender" is so terrible that I caught myself being genuinely surprised when I saw that our attacker managed to outrun one of the opponent's players.
The first signs
The COVID-19 pandemic is slowing down, but experts do not expect a major turnaround in the coming weeks.
According to statistical models, the pressure on hospitals will remain for some time, and a new unknown has been added to the pandemic equation: the omicron variant, which is very likely to spread faster than the currently predominant Delta.
At the same time, it is not yet possible to say with absolute certainty whether it can cause a more serious course, how much it is helped by vaccination or post-infectious immunity acquired by a previous illness.
This week, however, an unexpected phenomenon has entered the Covid equation on the plus side: the possibility of treatment.
A new drug, the antiviral molnupiravir, has arrived in the Czech Republic, which reduces the risk of severe illness and hospitalisation by a third and can be taken at home.
It will soon be joined by Pfizer's paxlovid drug, which reports a success rate of 85 per cent.
The first deliveries of molnupiravir to the Czech Republic have not only raised hopes of expanding the portfolio of tools useful in the fight against the coronavirus pandemic, but have also highlighted the question of how the Czech administration is prepared for the arrival of new drugs.
As mentioned, the first one to reach Czech patients will be Merck's molnupiravir.
The company ended up at the front of the line in part because the drug was already in development long before the current pandemic to find a treatment for a viral disease in horses on the South American continent.
What is often overlooked in this research is that people in the West (Germany, Sweden, etc.)
are generally less open and do not share their views so openly.
On the other hand, Eastern Europeans, and especially we Czechs, are used to saying "as if a beak grew on our nose".
So you do research where you ask people if they like Muslims.
In the Czech Republic, most people will tell you straight up that they don't.
In the West, they'll tell you how much they love migration, how everyone should help them, and how we Czechs are racist scumbags.
And then they go and vote for a party like the AfD.
They fear cancel culture - saying this in public means losing your job and being mobbed by the media.
Then it looks nice in the polls, west good, east bad.
But it really finds out what people think.
