We even know that there are three of them and that they are completely identical.
Identical due to the rotation of the units so that the soldiers don't have to relearn where everything is, all the buildings are almost exactly the same.
One is the Atom Museum Brdy and the other two are abandoned.
The funny thing is that the USSR did not want to have nuclear warheads on its own territory, either for security reasons or because of the speed of deploying warheads due to its western location.
Only the warheads were stored in the underground shelters (there are two in each maple tree) and not the entire missiles as is said.
If it was necessary to deploy this weapon, a special unit would have been called in to pick up the warhead and mount it on some kind of delivery system.
In addition to the museum maple, the rest are in a dilapidated state.
In elementary school, we had a Gypsy classmate for 4 years.
He was pretty good, he made some good jokes, he was often too talkative, but he was like our mascot.
Everyone was talking to him, he often came back and wanted to explain something, he was almost always here, he engaged in sport with us, he didn't steal snacks or mobile phones, he came dressed properly.
He went to nature schools, did all sorts of monkey business, but he was fine, he never got into any trouble.
In eighth or ninth grade, the siblings, the Roma, entered the same year, different classes.
Shortly afterwards, the teacher was beaten up, the police were often there, they were threatening and intimidating other students...
I sometimes sell things on classifieds (old stuff, things I don't need, etc.) and I've sold to Gypsies many times. They always had money, they didn't try to get me to lower the price, and the communication was calm.
I even sold a car this way, a guy called me a month later and said that he had already transferred it to himself...
I say myself that I'm not a racist, I don't care if someone is white, black, yellow, blue or other, as long as he behaves as he should in a decent society (works, functions, doesn't beat women, just normal behaviour).
But as soon as someone comes, they stretch out their hand, they move out of the apartments and houses, there's just a mess around them, they cause problems... it doesn't matter what colour they are, but it will bother me.
I have no problem with African migrants, if they get involved here, start a business, work, learn the language (not necessarily, at least English), and respect our culture.
I don't care if they believe in Allah, as long as they respect my traditions and culture, I will respect theirs too.
A young woman died in a car crash in Prachatice
"The young woman suffered serious multiple injuries and despite resuscitation efforts, sadly succumbed to her injuries at the scene," said Zuzana Fajtlová, a spokeswoman for the South Bohemian ambulance service.
The accident was probably caused by the driver who was taking the girl.
The 18-year-old driver of the Peugeot was probably driving from the village of Žíchovec to the village of Bavorov, and for unknown reasons, he left the road in a bend.
The Peugeot ended up on its roof off the road after the collision with the Skoda Octavia, described the accident by the spokesperson for the South Bohemian police, Štěpánka Schwarzová.
The young driver of the Peugeot was seriously injured in the accident.
He sustained multiple injuries and was trapped in the vehicle.
After his release, he had to be provided with emergency pre-hospital care, and, in a stable condition, he was airlifted to a hospital in České Budějovice, paramedic Fajtlová stated.
She added that the man in the second car suffered minor chest injuries and was taken to hospital.
New rules apply to parcels from non-EU countries, customers often do not provide information about them
Lukáš Neuheisl orders from abroad several times a month.
He mainly collects collector's cards.
"Usually, it can be tens of dollars, say from ten dollars up, where it is still worthwhile to import, especially from Japan, where postage is often free," says the collector.
Since October, ordering small parcels has become slightly more expensive, as he now has to add VAT, and the postal service has to submit data for customs proceedings.
He gets an email saying customs is awaiting the arrival of the package.
Then, all you have to do is fill in the information about the parcel, and if the seller did not include VAT in the sale, the customs authority will collect it from the total amount for the parcel and delivery.
In the case that the recipient does not take care of the customs procedure themselves, the total amount must also include the payment to the carrier.
According to Lukáš Neuheisel, however, the whole process is not complicated.
I tick one or two boxes, add two attachments and I'm done.
For me, it is usually a matter of five minutes, says Neuheisl.
Not all deliveries go smoothly, however.
As a result of the new customs regulations, the daily number of parcels received from abroad at the international post office in Prague has fallen from 60,000 to 15,000.
According to the Czech Post Office, the problem is also that people do not respond to requests for information needed to complete customs procedures.
There are currently 30,000 parcels waiting to be processed at the international post office.
If people filled in all the information that is required, and filled it in on time, we would be about halfway there, says Czech Post spokesman Matyáš Vitík.
