How to avoid drowning in the box tsunami
You open the gifts under the Christmas tree, and suddenly your house is full of boxes and packaging?
E-shops that lack packaging materials are making use of this "waste".
A map has been created of shops that will welcome your used boxes.
And not just at Christmas.
All packaging materials are designed to withstand repeated handling.
That's why it's a shame to treat them as single-use waste.
Anyone can bring cardboard boxes, plastic or paper filler to the participating store (the map of the project KAMsNIM.cz includes almost 150 of them).
This will support small businesses, reduce the amount of waste produced and also avoid overfilled blue bins.
The shops themselves welcome the packaging, which is currently in short supply on the market, as well as the saved money, as the price of the packaging cardboard has gone up by 50 per cent in the last period.
In the eyes of eco-conscious customers, I'm strengthening my brand.
One such business is TIERRA VERDE, a manufacturer of organic cosmetics and organic toiletries.
The boxes and the filler material are brought to us in Popůvky near Brno by individuals who have accumulated them at home, but we also hear from companies with which we have arranged regular collection of discarded cardboard.
We use it to pack orders from our e-shop.
Together, individuals and companies are creating a more compassionate world.
Our wish is to preserve the resources and beauty of nature for future generations, says Petra Lopušníková from Tierra.
However, the app www.KAMsNIM.cz shows not only collection points for packaging material.
It serves as a search engine if you need to get rid of anything (where to take separated household waste, where to hand in expired medicines, tyres, worn-out electrical appliances, batteries, light sources, bulky waste, etc.).
All waste can end up in the right place, and in addition, reusable items can find their second home.
The project's map already has more than 100,000 such places.
"Gradually, more and more collection yards, re-use centres, textile containers, food banks, charity shops, SWAPs and other places that help to find a use for things that would otherwise become waste are being set up there," adds Miroslav Kubásek, one of the authors of the application from the Ukliďme Česko (Clean up the Czech Republic) civic association.
I think it's wrong that today's technology is so simple and idiot-proof that children who use computers or phones to play games don't learn basic computer skills.
There has been a recent problem (especially in English articles) that university students do not understand the principle of components on a computer.
Because, for example, Google Photos or Apple's photos app or indeed mobile phones in general just hide the underlying filesystem with its folders and throw everything onto one screen in an app.
They can use the technique from their childhood, but most of all, they should learn something.
Let's rewrite history, seriously
Emmanuel Macron unveiled the priorities of the French EU presidency - which begins in January - at the weekend, and it was spectacular.
Macron spoke for over an hour, during which he unveiled the logo for the presidency, called for the protection of Europeans - at work, on the street - and mentioned so many actions that they cannot be completed in half a year.
French politicians love it, and so do the voters.
Macron's supporters, split between right and left, agree on very little, but they do agree on Europe.
And in France, there will be new elections for the head of state in April.
The election calendar also influenced the priorities themselves.
The French leader, among other things, mentioned that historians should write "one history of Europe" and France is prepared to create conditions for such work by historians.
Several commentators were quick to criticize Macron for pro-European propaganda and rewriting history.
In fact, it is trying to prevent the rewriting of history.
The far-right candidate for the French presidency, Éric Zemmour, is currently touring France with the thesis that the Vichy regime, which collaborated with Hitler during World War II, was not so bad, and he has some success with the French people.
Let us take Macron's idea of a single history textbook seriously and not look at what is happening in France.
Would it not be needed?
Students in European countries are often taught history as a story of us versus them and never as a story of the whole.
Spaniards, French and Czechs learn who defeated whom in which battle.
But if they don't have a wise cantor, they won't learn the broader context of the event.
