The trains start running according to the new timetable, in some places the operators will change
From Sunday, trains will run according to the new timetable on the railways.
The biggest change is the replacement of carriers on some routes, for example between Ústí nad Labem and Kolín, where instead of ČD, RegioJet will start operating.
For most of the lines, only the departure time will be changed, and the route will be changed only slightly.
There will also be tens of new trains on the tracks.
The transport companies started to sell tickets already in the autumn.
Czech Railways are planning to run an average of 6,783 passenger trains a day in the new timetable, including an average of 478 long-distance trains a day.
During the new timetable, trains will cover approximately 118 million kilometres.
In addition to domestic connections, the new timetable will also include routes to Germany, Poland, Slovakia, Hungary, Austria and Switzerland.
The company is introducing dozens of new trains as part of the new timetable.
The main innovation will be the InterJet trains, which will run on the Prague-Cheb route.
The other new trains will be deployed in northern Moravia or western Bohemia.
The transport company will also traditionally increase ticket prices next year, by an average of 3.2 percent.
The railways take inflation into account in their fares every year.
The biggest change in the RegioJet timetable is the introduction of the R23 Ústí nad Labem – Mělník – Nymburk – Kolín line.
The transport company will replace České dráhy following its success in the Ministry of Transport’s competition.
RegioJet will run a total of 16 trains a day, eight in each direction.
Other changes affect long-distance services between Prague and Brno, which from Sunday will also stop at Havlíčkův Brod, Žďár nad Sázavou and Kolín.
Leo Express has kept its 16 connections, two return connections to Slovakia and weekend connections to Krakow.
According to the spokesperson, Emil Sedlárik, the transport company tried to keep the departure times of its long-distance trains as similar as possible despite the planned strike action.
The operation of Arriva and other train operators should continue without major changes.
The transport operator will also be replaced on some regional lines.
There will be changes for travellers, for example in Českolipsko, where instead of the Czech Railways, the Trilex trains of the German company Die Länderbahn will run on the route from Mladá Boleslav via Česká Lípa to Rumburk.
Passengers will also be able to use a single ticket on the railways in the second year.
Like the Czech Railways, their price will increase by inflation of 3.2 percent.
I have to disagree.
Don't we learn from the other side's point of view?
Everywhere we hear about how hard they had to fight for their rights, how they were oppressed and had to work hard and die.
In my lifetime, I have never heard a teaching from the perspective of the slave's side or from that time. No one is defending it, just condemning it.
No one tells you in school that black people often sold other black people into slavery, and that they were often the worst slavers.
No one teaches you at school that the colonisers often bought the land from the Indians; all they tell you is how brutally we, the Europeans, exterminated them, while they were already killing each other.
I also spent some time in the USA, directly in the schools, both in the north and in the south.
I have not come across anyone deliberately covering up facts, but I have heard of it happening in the past, and I think it is a problem, and I don't deny it (e.g. in Japan, WW2 atrocities are a bit of a taboo).
My point was more that history isn't black and white, and we tend to look at it through a modern lens without understanding.
History doesn't care about people's feelings, it is what it is and I think it's a fatal error to judge without looking at it in the context of the time.
On the other hand, we should learn from it and never do it again.
By the way, while we're on the subject of the southern states, yes, the Confederate flag and famous slave owners are quite popular there, on the other hand, they also had some good successes, and it seemed absurd to me to reject them.
Moreover, the North was not much better, as many people idealize it today.
And a lot of people also forget that not everyone in the South was a slave owner, and a lot of things went against them as well.
I wouldn't compare this to the Russians, they deliberately omit some facts, they lie and manipulate, moreover, our point of view doesn't exist there (there was a video on YT from a TV station where someone was silenced who started talking about our legionaries and 1968).
What I found funny about US schools was the rise of Marxism and the idealization of communism, something that their country has never experienced.
Overall, I found that at some universities it was terrible, those students were pretty radicalized, and those schools often supported them in it.
