TV has abandoned the Christmas movie trend, with 200 new ones premiering this year
Los Angeles - Movie theaters, television networks and streaming platforms in the United States and other English-speaking countries have fallen for the trend of Christmas movies and this year are premiering a record more than 200 to their viewers.
The operator of the IMDb film database counted them.
The genre of Christmas family and romantic films has been scoring with the public in recent years and has seen a significant increase in viewership, so more and more of these films are being made.
This year, four times as many Christmas films were made as in 2011 and twice as many as five years ago.
The IMDb database, however, only counts those films that have the word Christmas in their title, so there are actually a lot more Christmas movies out there.
The movies that people traditionally associate with Christmas have always been there.
In the Czech Republic, this period is mainly associated with fairy tales, while around the world, films such as Home Alone, Love Actually or the classic Christmas story It's a Wonderful Life from 1946 are popular.
The real boom in Christmas films began in 2009, when the American cable television channel Hallmark came up with a special film series, the BBC website recalled.
Her Christmas project called Countdown to Christmas included four films and was very successful.
This year, the station started to tune its viewers in for Christmas on October 22, and will present a total of 42 Christmas films.
Competitor network Lifetime has 35 new holiday-themed films on its schedule this year, and popular streaming platforms like Netflix are also contributing to the overall total.
"At this magical time of year, it doesn't matter so much about the story, it's just important that there's a lot of Christmas trees in the background and it's snowing," said Brandon Gray, author of the book I'll Be Home for Christmas Movies.
"For the audience, it's a form of escape and a way to feel a little bit of respite for at least two hours in the midst of all of the craziness of the holidays and the craziness of the world we've been living in for the past couple of years," Gray added.
According to him, for example, the Hallmark channel uses the same recipe for its films, which is uniform, but successful.
You have two people who fall in love, but then, about half an hour before the end, there is a misunderstanding, which is successfully resolved and the two of them kiss.
That's the way it goes round and round, and as long as all the films look the same and have the same atmosphere, people are going to watch them one after another, adds Gray.
