California will limit gun sales.
It wants to follow Texas' lead on abortion bans.
California Gov. Gavin Newsom on Saturday announced a plan to ban the sale and manufacture of some guns in the nation's most populous state using the legal mechanism Texas used in its controversial abortion law that bans the procedure once a fetal heartbeat is detected.
People would then be able to sue anyone who manufactures or sells assault weapons or homemade firearms in California for damages.
Newsom's announcement came in response to a Friday ruling by the U.S. Supreme Court that allowed a Texas abortion ban to remain in place, despite being at odds with a nearly 50-year-old precedent that established the right to an abortion nationwide through about the 24th week of pregnancy.
However, the court was not ruling on the constitutionality of the entire law, but on a technical issue arising from the innovative design of the measure.
In this case, however, enforcement of the ban was handed over to the public, making it impossible for the Texas Republicans to challenge it through the courts.
"I am outraged by yesterday's (Friday) U.S. Supreme Court decision to allow Texas' ban on most abortions to remain in place and to largely endorse Texas' maneuver to protect its law," the California governor said.
"If states can now block review of their laws by federal courts, California will use that authority to save lives," Newsom continued.
He reportedly told his subordinates to work with the state parliament and the justice minister on a measure that would allow citizens to enforce the ban on assault rifles and so-called ghost guns.
These are home-made weapons that have no serial numbers and can be used to circumvent regulations.
Newsom wants to give "private citizens" the right to demand damages of at least $10,000 and court costs from anyone who manufactures, distributes or sells assault rifles, "ghost gun" parts or kits to make them in California.
"If the most effective way to keep these deadly weapons off our streets is to create a private right of action, then that's exactly what we should do," the California governor said.
The AP notes that California has banned the manufacture and sale of some military-style weapons for decades, but a federal judge blocked the state's ban as unconstitutional in June.
If the state were now to reinstate the ban using the Texas model, it would confirm the words of liberal Supreme Court Justice Sonia Sotomayor, who in a dissent to Friday's majority ruling warned against expanding the legal mechanism to other U.S. states.
The Supreme Court, however, did not give Texas's abortion ban total immunity from judicial review, allowing abortion clinics to proceed with lawsuits against select officials in the southern U.S. state.
