Poland threatens to stop paying into EU budget
According to Ziobro, the European Commission would be acting against the law if it were to use its new powers to stop the payment of money to Poland due to a dispute over the rule of law.
The Commission has already delayed the approval of the Polish plan to draw 36 billion euros from the EU fund for the recovery of economies hit by the Covid-19 pandemic.
And it is under pressure from the European Parliament to go further and use a mechanism that can withhold EU funds from countries that break the rule-of-law principles.
"Poland should respond to this blackmail by the EU with a veto in all matters that require unanimity," said Ziobro, head of the small Solidarna Polska party, without whose votes the current government would lose its narrow majority in the lower house of parliament.
"Poland should also consider its obligations in the EU's energy and climate policy, which lead to a drastic increase in energy prices," added Ziobro.
If the dispute continues, I will ask Poland to stop its contributions to the EU.
It would be justified given the fact that the EU is illegally withholding funds from the common budget to which we also contribute, added the Polish minister.
Its approach to the EU is more radical than that of the ruling Law and Justice party.
According to the European Commission, the changes to the Polish justice system during Ziobro's tenure threaten its independence and subordinate it to politicians.
According to Ziobro, Brussels is setting "impossible conditions, because its goal is not a state of law, but a change of government in Poland".
Warsaw is facing a "political dictatorship enforced by blackmail and a bid to overturn the democratic decision of several million Poles," Ziobro also said.
