When I was a child, I was punished with a wooden spoon.
It was never about the grades, it was mostly because I repeatedly refused to listen and misbehaved (read instead of going to bed, argued with my brother, etc).
At the same time, I have never been punished without a warning. My mother always threatened that if I do it again, I will get a spanking (and sometimes, even after another "scolding" with the spoon, she only brought it and placed it so that I could see it).
Only after I repeatedly refused to listen did I get a few slaps on the butt (through clothing).
I personally think that physical punishment (in a reasonable manner and to a reasonable extent) is beneficial, because the child reacts to it much more than to words.
I think the important part is the warning section, because it gives the child a way to choose whether or not to ignore it and get it, or to improve and not get the punishment.
I usually only needed a warning before I started listening.
Defence of the system
When the prominent Czech lawyer and constitutional court judge Vojtěch Cepl answered a journalist's question in 1999 about what the Czech constitution meant to him - whether it was a sacred document to which one swore an oath and which one was taught about at school from a young age, or, on the contrary, an agreement that can be changed if necessary - he definitely favoured the former.
We once agreed in the constitution on the democratic rules of our life, which at the same time define who we are as a state and its citizens, and it is better to avoid changes.
And imagine: some nations actually like their rules.
Just like Czechs like dumplings with pork and cabbage, Vojtěch Cepl said back then.
However, lawyers are increasingly of the opinion that the Czech Constitution needs to be changed.
Over the years, it has been tested by situations that its creators (including Vojtěch Cepl) could not predict, such as the behaviour of the directly elected president.
However, Cepl was right about one thing.
Everything we know about such documents suggests that political interventions in their texts must be deliberate.
The Institute needs to be understood and actively defended, only then can it be the key to dealing with most of the crises that have faced societies throughout history.
A constitution is, among other things, a set of rules of government, which sets limits on what politicians can do.
We are afraid that it will be misused against minorities or individuals, so we tie the politicians' hands with prohibitions.
At the same time, the constitutional texts also allow politicians to use their power.
Covid doesn't discriminate, several-month-old baby is fighting for its life in Brno University Hospital
Although it is known that the coronavirus is less severe in children, there are also severe cases that the hospital has been dealing with mainly recently.
"We know that children are at less risk and are less affected than adults. We talk about 2 to 5 percent compared to adults," said Petr Dominik, Head of the Clinic of Paediatric Anaesthesiology and Resuscitation at Brno University Hospital and Faculty of Medicine at Masaryk University, to Novinky.
The course is usually much simpler, lighter, and often symptom-free.
But there are children who are severely affected by the coronavirus, which we have seen, especially in recent times," added Dominik.
According to the doctor, it is about dozens of children who need mild supportive care.
It takes place at a children's infectious disease clinic.
Children who are very seriously ill with the coronavirus have only recently been admitted to the ICU.
Children with post-Covid syndromes have been admitted to the ward continuously throughout the year, according to the doctor.
"Now we're seeing an increase in children with acute COVID pneumonias, which means an inflammation of the lung that requires a stay in the intensive care unit," he said, adding that the illness affects not only adults but also adolescents and infants as young as a few months old.
Children are also in critical condition due to COVID-19 in hospitals.
"We currently have a child of several months of age and an adolescent in our care," said the director.
However, she is pleased that the children's hospital at FN Brno has not recorded any child deaths from the coronavirus.
According to the available data, six children aged 0 to 14 died in the Czech Republic by December 6.
According to Dominik, in a children's hospital - not just in the coronavirus department - a psychologist is an integral part of the team.
It also points out that just like in adults, vaccination also reduces the severity of the disease and the incidence of post-COVID-19 syndrome in children.
"That's why we recommend the vaccine for children as well," the doctor added.
