Holland was also sentenced to 120 hours of unpaid work, she was banned from keeping animals for life and must pay 12,000 Czech crowns in court costs.
Leader of the Small Monkeys team that rehabilitated the abused animal, Steph Sawyer, said: "Milly is doing well but the rehabilitation will continue."
It took Milly a while to get used to people again.
She cowered and hid from everyone she met, and any loud sound or sudden movement caused her to scream.
The monkey refused to eat for a long time.
Even now, when she's settled and happy with her mate, the sight of new people can still send her into a panic.
The psychological scars of the abuse will stay with her forever, Sawyer adds.
The abuse of Milly came to light when police in Gwent found the shocking footage on the woman's phone following a drugs raid on her home.
The footage shows Milly using vulgar language.
In another video, Ms. Holland is heard offering the monkey cocaine, saying, "Do you want some cocaine?"
