More than 60 per cent of voters turned out for Saturday's elections to the councils of four municipalities
On Saturday, new councillors were elected in the municipalities of Komňa in Uherskohradišť district, Lužice in the Most district, Nová Ves in the Liberec district and in Rovné in the Pelhřimov district.
The number of representatives in these municipalities has fallen below the number set by law, or the elected council has collapsed.
A total of 99 candidates competed for the 28 seats on Saturday.
The average age of the newly elected representatives is 46.7 years.
The oldest is 69 years old, the youngest 33 years old.
Processing the results of Saturday's elections symbolically closes a fairly difficult, but successful year for us.
There were a total of four new or repeat elections to municipal councils, and the very closely watched elections to the Chamber of Deputies, said the deputy chairwoman of the Czech Statistical Office, Eva Krumpová.
She pointed out that due to the COVID-19 pandemic, the elections were more challenging in terms of equipment and personnel security.
In Komňa, in Uherskohradišť, Saturday's election was won by the Association of Independent Candidates, which won 27.76 percent of the votes and two seats in the seven-member council.
The STAN candidate received 24.84% of the votes, which also means two seats.
Two seats in the council were also won by Občané pro Komňu, who received 18.52 percent of the vote.
Jana Křižková, the current mayor of the town, who is a member of the Soukromníci party, was also re-elected to the council.
Komňané - independent candidates - won one seat on the council.
75.48 per cent of the eligible voters cast their votes.
The association Pro Rovnou won in the village of Rovná in Pelhřimov.
It won 50.50% of the votes, which means four seats out of seven.
Two representatives from the Association of Independent Candidates 1 and one from the Association of Independent Candidates 2 were also elected to the municipal council.
Turnout was 93.62 percent.
The Lužice and Svinčice association, led by mayor Jindřich John, again won the repeated elections in Lužice on Mostecko.
It received 56.73% of the votes and, just like in 2018, it has four seats in the seven-member council.
The second place went to Obec pro lide, which received 43.27 percent of the vote, and will have three representatives in the council.
76.7% of voters went to the polls.
Independent candidates Naděje pro Novou Ves won the election in Nová Ves, Liberec, ahead of the ANO movement.
The association of independent candidates received 59.88 per cent of the vote and won four of the seven seats in the municipal council.
ANO received 40.12 percent of the votes and strengthened against the regular elections in 2018, gained one more mandate and now has three.
Turnout was 42.9 per cent of voters.
On Monday, the State Election Commission will discuss the election results.
They will then be published in the Collection of Laws.
