He then knocked him down with a series of well-aimed blows to record his 15th triumph.
Kara-France then beat Cody Garbrandt.
In the spring, Nunes celebrated another triumph with her little daughter, now, after seven years, she has lost.
That hip or this hip?
At first glance, it's not complicated.
Most nouns in Czech express only one grammatical gender, so there is no problem in determining whether it is masculine, feminine, or neuter.
There is, however, also a relatively large group of nouns whose gender is not fixed.
Such substantives vacillate between two genders.
When inflected, they take on double endings, and in some cases, remain in the uninflected form.
For example, the words "svížel" and "kyčel" are both of the masculine and feminine gender, in the first one it is declined according to the model "stroj", in the second one according to the model "píseň".
In another group of nouns, the forms are different even in the first case singular, for example: "řádek/řádka", "kedluben/kedlubna" or "brambor/brambora" (in the sense of food).
Both forms are standard, have the same meaning, and are thus freely interchangeable.
Some words can vary regionally, for example, "okurka" in Bohemia and "okurek" in Moravia, but in this case, the Moravian variant is incorrect, as is the case with other Czech-Moravian pairs of words: "příkop" and "příkopa", "kobliha" and "koblih", and so on.
Some words that have entered the Czech language from other languages were originally uninflected, but they are now gradually taking on Czech endings.
A typical example is the word "image", which is both masculine and feminine, or the word "buffet", which remains in the middle gender and is not declined in the masculine, but has endings like "castle".
