Scattered houses flood the Czech Republic, families have no money to complete them
The price of building materials has increased by more than 30 per cent in recent weeks and months.
It has put a lot of people in a difficult situation.
He does not have the means to finish the family homes he has laid out and the banks are refusing to increase his mortgage.
In addition to the cost of materials, the cost of construction work is increasing.
People therefore do not have enough money to complete the family homes that have already been laid out.
In many cases, banks are refusing to increase mortgage loans, which creates an extremely unpleasant situation.
At best, people are moving into houses that are scattered and not finished.
In the worst case, the houses are empty and families are forced to sell them because they cannot afford to pay off the mortgage and rent at the same time," says BHS economist Štěpán Křeček.
We build two to three family houses a year and for fifty percent of them, this has happened.
It's hard for us as a construction company, because we have to honour some things contractually, even though the materials have gone up in price.
So we do it for free," said construction company owner Zdeněk Slivoň.
A lot of people are going to have financial problems.
If they were counting on the house costing five million, now it will cost seven.
I think some will wait and see," Slivoň added.
The most expensive materials were copper, iron and also plumbing and heating equipment.
Construction firms are also struggling with a lack of labour.
The Czech Republic is short of construction graduates and the influx of foreign workers has been hindered by the pandemic.
At this moment, the situation is only more favourable in terms of issuing building permits.
"In October, building authorities issued 7,675 building permits, which is almost 10 percent more than a year ago," said Křeček.
We're doing well and we'll do even better.
