After a few years of dormancy and suppression of this illegal business, MLM recruiting is back in the limelight.
I was one of the recruits, I tried it (I was 20 years old, a first-year student at university), the initial promises of training in products and business skills quickly turned into "it doesn't matter to you, just get people".
I was genuinely interested in the products I was offering, as I wanted to help people, but the training was more about how to scare and talk people into buying.
When the first money came in, you quickly realized that if you wanted to make money, you had to push a few certain products a month.
Investment life insurance and mortgages were the only things that paid, so you felt like a travelling pot salesman.
However, I can say that it was a valuable experience, and I learned not to jump on every piece of gossip and to check information thoroughly.
At the same time, I wouldn't put them all in one bag.
There are people in this business who are successful and even beneficial to people, but they certainly won't boast of expensive consumer goods or a "fat" account.
In the corporation where I work, I have not seen so many of these things.
HR is calm, the managers look after their management and they don't stick their nose into anything.
Regular assessment does happen, in the form that it happens here (set yourself some goals for next year, in a year's time we'll see what worked and what didn't) - it's more of a self-assessment than someone assessing you based on some numbers, and so on.
Company outings are also optional.
But we are a bit unique within our company - there are departments that are more "corporate".
There are times when you feel like we're some kind of quasi-startup, squatting in the offices of a big corporation.
But it doesn't bother us that much as long as the results are there.
