How the pandemic has affected your sex life: More people under 35 are having no sex at all for a year
More and more young adults in the U.S. are living their lives without sex.
They are mainly religious people, according to the DailyMail website.
The survey showed that from 2008 to 2021, the share of people under 35 who abstained from sex rose from eight to 21 percent.
Women aged 18 to 35 who say they haven't had sex in the past year are at an all-time high.
The decline in the number of sexually active individuals is also due to other factors, according to a survey by the Institute for Family Studies (IFS).
One of them could be the economic impact of the coronavirus pandemic and a higher percentage of unemployment.
However, the presence of the media, social networks and video games, which make sex less and less of a priority for young people, could also be a factor.
"Since 2010, there has been a rapid rise in the share of men and women aged 18-35 who say they had no sex in the past year," said IFS researcher Lyman Stone.
Married people are more likely to be sexually active, with just 5 per cent saying they had not had sex in the last year in 2021.
Among the unmarried, it was 29 percent. Mr. Stone added that marriages under 35 were only a small percentage.
The decrease in sexual activity is also caused by the fear of premarital sex and religious beliefs.
Despite being more likely to be sexually active, the proportion of married and cohabiting under-35s is still falling.
Young people's views on pre-marital sex are split, with about 30% seeing it as wrong and about 70% as acceptable.
"It's true that they're a minority among singles in this age group, but their behavior is shifting the trend," Stone says of the 30 percent.
For most of those who have a moral problem with premarital sex, the reason is a religious upbringing.
Among single people under 35 who attend religious services more than once a month, the proportion abstaining has risen from 20 per cent to almost 60 per cent since 2008.
The trend among the "less religious" has risen from 10 to 20 percent," Stone said.
Other factors, such as less social interaction and social drinking during the pandemic, also contributed to the decline in sexual activity.
The study also found that people who are unemployed or have lower incomes are less likely to be sexually active.
Another reason could be the expansion of digital media, which seems to reduce the need for sex.
People are spending more time online, which "substitutes" for this need.
This trend has taken hold mainly during the lockdown in the time of the coronavirus pandemic.
The whole COVID vaccine mandate is about whether or not society should force a portion of the population to do something they don't want to do, but that could save their lives.
It's a pretty heavy question, and the one I'm personally most interested in is the question of social conscience.
That is to say, for example, the question of whether if we don't tell them and they die, it will be our fault.
My argument is that we could certainly have prevented the death of an 80-year-old who really didn't know much, we didn't explain it well to him, he heard some misinformation, and as a result he didn't get vaccinated and ended up catching it and dying.
On the other hand, I do not think that we can blame the death of a determined opponent of vaccination, who has been ranting about bullying and a totalitarian state alongside the SPD and the KSČ.
From the statistics I mentioned, it is quite clear that the majority of the unvaccinated pensioners probably belong to the second group, so they will actually have to pay for it themselves.
