The dog, Hugo, is doing his best.
However, Juraj Šajmovič did not keep an eye on his film.
Czech creators of family comedies have been inspired by American stories about pampered dogs.
But they forgot one important thing: the laws of film-making.
After F. Brabce's cheesy film, Gump - the dog who taught people to live, another film, Here We Watch Over You, is now vying for the audience's emotions in cinemas.
Co-screenwriter and director in one person, Juraj Šajmovič Jr. follows up on his previous film Tady hlídám já from 2012.
The talking hedgehog Hugo is returning to the stage, along with some familiar characters.
Julie and Ivan, owners of a dying Šumava guest house, start inviting dog walkers, Julie's father with his partner and especially her daughter Veronika.
She is no longer a little girl, but a young woman experiencing her first love.
The director and his partner, Beatriz Šajmovičová (who is also the film's producer), struggled with the storytelling in their previous canine film, but at least the children and the dog had fun there.
This time, the creative duo have written an even weaker script that elicits a mixture of fear and feelings of embarrassment.
Let's recap.
Julie, despite being a scientist, succumbs to the darkness of her desire for a child and when the right "constellation" occurs, she copulates with her forest engineer Ivan anywhere the coordinates indicate - on the hood of a car or a church tower (of course during an ongoing tour with a local guide), the retired colonel Mojmír, despite years of training, shoots his own daughter (Julie) in the forest, who falls into a coma, after which she is taken from the hospital by the family so that the miraculous process of healing by dogs can take place in the heart of a Bohemian wilderness.
Nothing wrong with a bit of nature therapy and the power of a pet animal's love.
Their owners know why they have them.
But the viewer can't help but wonder how much content pelmel full of implausible situations and figures was needed for this message.
A pair of staff thieves, a dog show, a South Bohemian charlatan, police officers arriving to search for "drugs" and discussing the fertilising power of bone meal over herbs - and, of course, the baked family in the pension getting drunk.
When the protagonist, after a long coma, wakes up and immediately sits at the family table, half-naked and made-up, with a cigarette in her hand, and demands her father's whisky and a bit of gossip, as if she were a recovered vegetarian, you can't help but laugh.
On top of that, the creators explain to the viewer that "this sometimes happens after a coma."
Šajmovič's team lacks the basic dramaturgical knowledge of working with text, the ability to build up the main situations, a sense for the characters and the point, and directorial guidance.
The acting is uneven, the editing aimless and the overall impression muddled.
As much as Lukáš Vaculík, Jitka Ježková or Nela Boudová try to keep their parties going, they don't have much to play with.
The only positive aspect of the film are the poetic shots of the Šumava nature by cameraman Vladimír Holomek and the pair of ferrets.
It is not enough to outline a few characters, a flimsy plot, and dog jokes, not to mention the more common vulgar expressions that the characters use.
It is not even a long-standing membership in the Dachshund Breeder's Club, as in the case of the lady producer.
Behind the good intentions to promote nature and the friendship between man and dog, there must also be knowledge of the craft, if one wants to tell a credible story.
This was not the case this time.
There's a bit too much erotica and not enough feeling for the genre in a good family photo.
Even as an advertisement for canine therapy, this amateurish piece wouldn't pass muster.
