The Middle East is experiencing unusually dry months.
Winter is the only time of the year when it rains.
"The almost complete absence of rainfall during November, as recorded at some stations, is unusual," confirms the Israel Meteorological Service.
For example, the village of Kfar Giladi in northern Israel reports only six percent of its long-term average rainfall for November.
This week's two-day rain was therefore more of an exception.
It's good for us.
It hadn't rained for a long time.
It's also the right Christmas backdrop, rejoiced Nazareth resident Wasim Aškar.
Rainfall in Israel comes almost exclusively in the winter months, is sporadic and unpredictable.
Forests depend on winter rains.
Without them, they dry out and become prone to fires.
It's not just about forests, but also drinking water supplies and irrigation for farmers.
Israel's largest freshwater source, the Sea of Galilee, is this spring full to the brim after three consecutive rainy winters.
Since then the level has been falling.
The water authorities have been warning of a drought for a long time.
"It is expected that, due to global warming and climate change, there will be less rainfall here," Uri Schor, a spokesperson for the Israel Water Authority, said in 2018.
Israel can help with technologies such as desalination and waste-water recycling.
Economically weaker countries such as Lebanon, Syria and Jordan are worse off.
In the streets of Jordan's capital, Amman, there are more tanker trucks.
Water mains and private wells are drying up.
"This year, my orders have gone up by 70 to 80 percent compared to the previous two years," tanker driver Imad Suleiman said in September.
In Iran's Isfahan, clashes broke out between farmers and security forces.
The cause of the protests was the drought.
The bed of the local river was completely dry.
The region has experienced its driest November in many recent years.
