Another government ends and the law on the involvement of municipalities in the selection of a repository is nowhere to be found
Minister Karel Havlíček's draft needs a major overhaul
The government of Prime Minister Andrej Babiš is coming to an end, and the law that was supposed to ensure the respect of the interests of municipalities and their citizens in the selection and licensing of a deep repository for high-level radioactive waste still does not exist.
The legislative council of the government interrupted the debate on the draft, which the Ministry of Industry and Trade presented to the government after years of delays.
Its content is, however, in serious contradiction not only with the affected municipalities associated in the Platform against the Deep Repository, but also with the Union of Towns and Municipalities of the Czech Republic.
Self-governing bodies are expecting a significant strengthening of their ability to decide on a storage facility, which has been promised to mayors since 2011, when the first work on this legislation began, and which is demanded by the Czech atomic law as well as the European directive.
We expect the new government, in line with its coalition agreement, to revise the proposal in cooperation with the municipalities.
The draft bill from Minister Karl Havlíček, which the Platform has access to, is criticised by municipalities for the following: The proposed level of involvement of municipalities and the public in the decision-making process regarding the selection of a site for a repository is insufficient and cannot ensure respect for the interests of municipalities and their citizens.
It can only be truly effective if the municipalities or the public can influence whether the process is continued in a given location.
This can be achieved by placing a duty on the Storage Authority to obtain the approval of the affected municipalities before a specific procedure is initiated.
The proposed proposal for a regulation almost completely neglects the involvement of the public and makes the citizens of the municipalities practically mere statistics in the permitting procedures.
The proposal is missing the systematic setting of compensations for municipalities for the entire process of finding and selecting a site for a repository, its permitting and operation.
According to today's laws, representatives of municipalities do not have many options to defend the interests of their citizens when looking for a site for a storage facility.
Only in some permit proceedings can they submit comments or appeal, but the authority or the minister in whose interest the permit is issued makes the decision.
A potential lawsuit will not have a suspensive effect on the implementation of survey or construction works.
The co-determination of local authorities, which the Platform is asking for, is a common principle used in many democratically advanced countries, and certainly in those which have already progressed in allowing storage, such as Sweden and Finland.
The preparation of the law is another failure of the state administration, which hires external law firms to prepare the legislation.
In this case, it is a contract with the law firm HAVEL & PARTNERS s.r.o., which was concluded by SÚRAO, following contracts with lawyer Jan Zemánek.
According to the register of contracts, the total sum for this work is almost 4 million Czech crowns.
Antonín Seknička, deputy mayor of the village of Cejle in the Hrádek area and spokesperson for the Platform Against the Deep Repository, said: After the ministers of industry who only passed on the task of finding a deep repository for high-level radioactive waste to their successors, we expect a more decisive turn from the new government.
We also offer a helping hand.
We would also like to thank the Association of Towns and Municipalities, which views the problem of inadequate rights of municipalities in relation to such an important construction in the same way as the directly affected municipalities in selected locations.
The platform against the deep repository unites 51 members (35 municipalities and towns and 16 associations) in order to promote a change in the state's approach to handling spent nuclear fuel and other radioactive waste, which will not be limited to the deep repository.
The platform also proposes that the decision to select a site for possible storage should be subject to the prior consent of the affected municipalities.
John Goodman (69) was scared into losing weight: He lost 90 kg.
Although he had no need to change his lifestyle for many years, in the end it was the doctors who scared him.
He was told if he didn't lose weight, he would die.
And that took time.
Goodman has lost 90 kilograms, which is half of his original weight of 180 kilograms, The Sun reports.
He boasted of his new figure in Los Angeles at the premiere of the animated series The Freak Brothers.
The fat guy from the Roseanne sitcom is a completely different person!
John liked to joke that his friends and family had begged him to lose weight because his large body was causing furniture to break.
"I was putting everything in my mouth," the actor said in a 2018 interview with AARP.
This time, I wanted to do it slowly.
Move, exercise.
I'm getting to the age where I can't afford to sit still, Mr. Goodman, whose transformation is remarkable, told ABC.
It also depends on what kind of boss and in what context you want to use the word "boss".
If it's some kind of text on a platform that expects readers from the gaming environment, I wouldn't translate it at all.
If it was, for example, a formal text and a university one, I would probably be looking for a way to describe or explain the boss.
To make matters worse, there are different kinds of bosses.
A game like Dark Souls, for example, has multiple bosses, right, and so a "boss" is kind of like the lord/ruler of a level, and then there's a final boss...
Many games feature hidden bosses (super boss, hidden boss), which are not required to be defeated in order to complete the game or level, but are often stronger than standard bosses.
Then there are games like Half-Life, where the bosses are there, but the player doesn't directly fight them (Tentacle, Gargantua), and can they be called bosses at all?
And then there are the mini-bosses.
It's not really possible to translate boss into one word in general, Czech and other languages don't solve it either (Catalan is interesting, for example, which translates boss as the final opponent).
It is, in short, a computer-controlled opponent significant to the story or the game in general, more powerful than all previous ones and guarding the completion of some level or task.
